{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c800bcf7-b57e-407a-b91f-01166650a0d8","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x dropped VSTest support by default.**\n\nStarting with MSTest.Sdk 4.0, the SDK exclusively uses **Microsoft Testing Platform** as the runner and no longer generates VSTest-compatible test host assemblies. This means `vstest.console` (and `dotnet test` in legacy mode) cannot discover or run your tests.\n\n**Your options:**\n\n1. **Switch your CI to `dotnet test`** (recommended) — it works with Microsoft Testing Platform natively in .NET 8+.\n\n2. **Run the test executable directly** — MSTest.Sdk 4.x projects produce a self-contained test app:\n   ```\n   dotnet build && ./bin/Debug/net8.0/TestProject.exe\n   ```\n\n3. **Re-enable VSTest compatibility** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\nThis lets `dotnet test` bridge to the new platform. However, `vstest.console.exe` itself is deprecated and won't be supported long-term — migrating away from it is the recommended path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc518c48-cd27-4aa8-ac9b-1ddcd5af3236","outputTokens":289,"requestId":"981C:32FC8B:53129C:6B30F2:69FFF6E5"},"id":"2a75e299-7af7-4ee5-8005-6106dee5791a","timestamp":"2026-05-10T03:09:34.487Z","parentId":"bc3d163f-e6fd-4d96-913e-66180dbd88b9"}
